by javiereguiluz at 2014-12-29T09:53:33Z

@karlosagudo first of all, congrats on your first PR!

As you may know, we have a robot called `fabbot` (not to be confused with the human `fabpot`) that automatically checks every submitted pull requests. One of the things checked by this robot is whether your code complies with the [Symfony Coding Standards](http://symfony.com/doc/current/contributing/code/standards.html). Right now it seems that your pull request doesn't comply with those standards, and hence the error shown by GitHub.

In order to fix this issues, you can check the [exact changes proposed by fabbot](http://fabbot.io/report/sensiolabs/SensioDistributionBundle/185/a4b36572e1c7128cc011ca2a21d0431338158575#patchcs). As you can see, it's a matter of refactoring the `if()...` in several lines. I know that this kind of changes may seem negligible, but using the same coding standard for all the code, makes the codebase more consistent and simplifies code reviewers work.

I also have two additional comments. First, I'd reword a bit the PHPdoc comment of the `getComposerVendorDir()` method the better explain its purpose. Here it is a proposal:

```
/**
 * In some special setups, the vendor/ directory isn't located in the project's
 * root directory. To make this command work for every case, read Composer's
 * vendor/ directory location directly from composer.json file.
 *
 * @return string
 */
```

The other thing I'd change is this line of code:

```php
$composerJson = json_decode(file_get_contents("../composer.json"));
```

We don't usually use relative dirs in the code and we always prefix them with `__DIR__`

